               <msContents>
                  <summary>The <title>Dābistān-i Maẕāhib</title> (School of Religions) recounts various religious creeds and philosophical systems of Asia, as known to the author, divided into twelve <hi rend="italic" xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">ta‘līm</hi>
                     (teachings) and subdivided into a various number of <hi rend="italic" xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">naẓar</hi>
                     (observations). The author, whose name appears here as <persName key="person_f3013" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Mīr Ẕū al-Fiqār ‘Alī al-Ḥusaynī (ca. 1615–70)</persName>, apparently followed the Āẕar Kayvānī illuminationist sect in India during the reign of the Mughal ruler ‘Ālamgīr I (r. 1658–1707). 
                     The author not only travelled throughout the northern <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName>, but also to Mashhad in Iran. 
                     As a result, he became thoroughly acquainted with a great number of religious and scientific Parsi, Hindu, Buddhist, Jewish, Christian, and Muslim personalities and their doctrines. . completed by <persName key="person_f1839" role="scr" change="#role-assignment">Kāshī Nath</persName> a Brahmin from city of <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1083799" key="place_1083799">Sialkot, Punjab</placeName> on the <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1796-03-24">15 Ramaz̤ān 1210 AH (24 Mar. 1796 CE)</date>.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_189-item1">
                     <author role="dub" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/47114320/" key="person_47114320">
                        <persName>Fānī, Muḥsin, d. 1671 or 2</persName>
                     </author>
                     <author key="person_f3013">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Mīr Ẕū al-Fiqār ‘Alī al-Ḥusaynī Ardistānī, ca. 1615–1670</persName><lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" type="org">ذو الفقار الحسینی</persName></author>
                     <author><persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="alt">Mūbad Shāh</persName><lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">مو بدشاه
                        </persName>
                     </author>
                     <editor key="person_f1839" role="scr" >
                        <persName xml:lang="hi-Latn-x-lc" change="#role-assignment">Kāshī Nath</persName> <foreign>کاشی ناته</foreign>
                     </editor>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_1537" change="#ids-cleanup">Dabistān</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_1537" change="#ids-cleanup">Tabṣirat al-Maz̲āhib va Taẕkira al-Adyān</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" key="work_1537" change="#ids-cleanup">دبستان</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" type="alt" key="work_1537" change="#ids-cleanup">تبصرت المذاهب و تذکرت الادیان</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" type="alt" key="work_1537" change="#ids-cleanup">Dabistān al-Maẕāhib</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" type="alt" key="work_1537" change="#ids-cleanup">Dabistān-i Maẕāhib</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar" type="basmalla"> ای نام تو سر دفتر اطفال دبستان * یاد ببالغ نظران شمع شبستان.</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar"/>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa"> نسخه دبستان مذاهب بخط بنده کاشی ناتهه (؟) قوم بر همن متوطن ملک پنجاب بلده سیالکوت تحریر پذیرفت پانزدهم شهر رمضان المبارک سنه ۱۲۱۰ هجری .</colophon>
                     <colophon>
                        Completed by <persName key="person_f1839" role="scr" change="#role-assignment">Kāshī Nath</persName>, a Brahmin from city of 
                        <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1083799" key="place_1083799">Sialkot, Punjab</placeName> onthe <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1796-03-24">15 Ramaz̤ān 1210 AH (24 Mar. 1796 CE)</date>.
                     </colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>This copy begins with a memorandum on the margins of folio:<lb/><q xml:lang="fa">محسن فانی گوید...</q><lb/>
                        (<q xml:lang="en">Muḥsin Fānī says...</q>) which may only refer to authorship of those verses, not the entire work. Former owner <persName>Samuel Hawtayne Lewin</persName>, citing Sir W. Ouseley (<title>Travels</title> vol. iii, p. 564), ascribes the work to Mubid Shah whom he distinguishes apart from Muhsin Fani as only the <q xml:lang="en">poet quoted at the beginning</q>, a view that comports with current scholarship. 
                        For other copies of this work, see Rylands <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7254"><idno>Persian MS 75</idno></ref> and <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6671"><idno>190</idno></ref>. 
                           Regarding the attribution of authorship for this work to <persName key="person_f3013" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" role="aut">Mīr Ẕū al-Fiqār ‘Alī al-Ḥusaynī Ardistānī</persName>, see Mojtabāʾī's overview.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
