                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink">
                        Copied in stylized <material>black</material> nasta‘līq with shikastah ligatures by <persName key="person_f1839" role="scr" change="#role-assignment">Kāshī Nath</persName>.<lb/>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions><lb/>
                     <!-- Check -->  <label>Table of Contents:</label> Listed on the initial flyleaves.<lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     A note penciled on the <locus>fly leaf</locus> suggests that it previously belonged to library of the Governor <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/19247044/" key="person_19247044" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment #ids-cleanup">Jonathan Duncan, 1756-1811</persName>
                     Some explanatory notes in English by <persName key="person_f2018" role="ann" change="#role-assignment">Lewin</persName>, who seems to agree with <name ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/18419237">Sir William Ouseley, 1767-1842</name>'s <title>Travels in Arabia</title> (iii, 564) in ascribing the work to <persName key="person_f3087" role="att" change="#role-assignment">Mūbid Shāh</persName>. He speaks of <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/47114320" key="person_47114320" role="att" change="#role-assignment #ids-cleanup">Muḥsin Fānī, -1671 or 1672</persName> to whom the work was previously ascribed as only the "poet quoted at the beginning".<lb/>
                     
                     <label>Bookplates</label> Bibilotheca Lindesiana, Bland MSS No. 410
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc><binding notBefore="1796-03-24" notAfter="1811">
                     <p>Possibly bound in a hybrid British-Indian style in the <placeName  ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001518">Bombay Presidency</placeName> for former owner <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/19247044" key="person_19247044">Jonathan Duncan (1756–1811)</persName> as the style comports with others that he formerly owned.</p>
                     <p>Resewn on three cord supports, frayed out and adhered to the first and last flyleaves.</p>
                     <decoNote type="binding"></decoNote>
                     <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                        <height>266</height>
                        <width>168</width>
                        <depth>45</depth>
                     </dimensions></p> 
                     <condition>Binding in good condition. White salts on the exterior, likely due to prolonged exposure to moisture.</condition>
                  </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
